                                                                                                               Nod for science hub degrees
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                               
	New Delhi, Aug. 20: The cabinet today approved legal amendments recognising degrees offered by the Indian Institutes of Science Education and Research (IISER), three years after the premier science hubs conceived by the Prime Minister took off.         
	The move ends a three-year wait by teachers, parents and over 550 elite students  picked for the institutions started to re-ignite interest in science and research in India  for legal sanctity to their courses.         
	The Telegraph had yesterday reported that the cabinet may today clear the amendments to the National Institutes of Technology Act of 2007, recognising the IISERs and legalising their degrees.         
	The IISERs  in Calcutta, Pune, Mohali, Trivandrum and Bhopal  offer unique five-year courses that combine undergraduate and masters education and offer a master in science (MS) degree.         
	The Calcutta and Pune institutes are the oldest  they started in 2006. The Mohali IISER started in 2007 and the remaining two last year.         
	The institutes, students and parents have been repeatedly petitioning the human resource development ministry for urgent recognition of their degrees.                                                                                                                                                                           
